From AIDS, non-communicable diseases in eight fundamental points
GENEVA - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as heart diseases, strokes, cancer, diabetes and chronic lung diseases are responsible for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that tobacco use, physical inactivity, poor diet and excessive alcohol consumption increase the chances of dying prematurely from non-communicable diseases.
Yet despite widespread knowledge of the risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to increase.
It is in this context that networks of alliances for non-communicable diseases met from December 9 to 11 at the Second World Forum of the Alliance on Non-Communicable Diseases in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions to regulate STIs, they should draw inspiration from the movement against AIDS.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to carry out interventions and their unique form of mobilization has been essential to the progress made.
Although the battle is not over, AIDS activists know that they can win this battle.
Similarly, a mobilization movement against STIs can turn back this epidemic.
Yet in 2015, Richard Horton, editor-in-chief of the journal The Lancet, described the STI community as waiting for "an electric shock to its semi-comatose mind." He added: "But who will have the courage to administer it?"
We believe there are lessons to be learned from AIDS activists.
While global attention focuses on the prevention of STIs, those seeking to control preventable diseases must look to the ABC of AIDS organizations.
The first letter the STI community must consider is « A », as in activism.
Anyone over 40 surely remembers the images of AIDS activists participating in « die-ins » during scientific meetings around the world.
In the United States, AIDS activists took to the streets, even shutting down the headquarters of the Food and Drug Administration for a day in October 1988.
On a a global scale, activists have pressured governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medicines more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Next, the NCD Community must adopt a bolder approach to budgets - the "B" of the AIDS fight movement's strategy.
Civic organization and grassroots activism can mobilize initial energies, but organizing and maintaining a broad coalition needs money.
The AIDS fight movement has been clear about this from the beginning and has pushed for resources to effectively support its awareness and accountability activities.
"C" represents coalitions: the movements fighting against AIDS quickly realized that progress only comes with multiple supports.
Activists have established links between people living with HIV and those with other concerns, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Coalitions and specialized campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders from the public authorities, in order to combine their viewpoints and expertise.
The AIDS fighting movement has also realized that a comprehensive response to the epidemic is essential for the spread of its support.
Thus, "D", the determining factor of success, consisted of 'drawing attention to the interconnectivity of the challenge.'
For example, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make intelligent decisions about when and with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
Similarly, links have been established between groups working on poverty, gender equality, and nutrition: all factors that have played a driving role in the AIDS crisis.
MNT are no less isolated in their causality and also undergo a multisectoral approach to prevention.
Engagement - "E" - is what has helped the AIDS movement gain such great influence.
Through strategic borrowings from the disability rights movement, which advocated the key phrase "Nothing about us without us," AIDS advocates have demanded the representation of existing organizations to deal with the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only United Nations agency with seats on its Board of Directors reserved for representatives of civil society.
This standard is so deeply embedded in the HIV/AIDS movement that it would almost be unthinkable for an HIV/AIDS meeting to take place without community representation.
Disease prevention movements must also develop compelling narratives and "F" - the framing of the issue - is essential for the HIV/AIDS community to gain political leaders' support.
In particular, access to HIV/AIDS treatment has been framed as an issue of economic justice.
Framing the narrative in this way has led to a significant reduction in drug prices, to the extent that more than half of people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are on treatment.
An equally important formulation of the issue for AIDS, a very relevant question for the MNT movement, is that of responsibility.
The AIDS community has worked hard to place more emphasis on people's life choices, rather than on the state's responsibility in providing healthcare and eliminating legal discrimination.
In the debate on AIDS, gender - the « G » of our movement - has been a significant point.
HIV was initially considered a « gay disease » and gender identity has been rooted in the DNA of the AIDS fight movement from the beginning.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: it is enough to look at how alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand this.
The genre, therefore, must become a focus of efforts to prevent MNT.
Finally, « H » - human rights - are the foundation of the response to AIDS.
Campaigns have been launched against discrimination at the workplace, in schools and in medical centers.
The strategic litigation has ensured equality under the law.
The AIDS struggle movement refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The MNT movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit the advertising of unhealthy foods for children.
We could continue listing the lessons learned from the fight against AIDS all the way through the alphabet, but we think it is appropriate to end on "H", given that human rights have provided the answer to AIDS and they should provide the answer to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization put people at greater risk of HIV.
The same applies to NCDs.
The first reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to ask: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The AIDS-fighting movement clearly stated that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet at risk of premature death due to preventable diseases, "these people" represent a large number of us.
The communities of MNT and AIDS can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our forces.
The opinions expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
